										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Yes, you can use AI bots for stock trading, but the real answer in 2026 is more specific than the marketing slogan. Most “AI stock trading bots” do one of four jobs: generate signals, test strategies, automate execution, or route alerts into a broker. What makes this question especially timely is that U.S. equities are moving toward much longer trading windows. Nasdaq received SEC approval in April 2026 to extend trading to 23 hours a day, five days a week; NYSE Arca says it is targeting nearly continuous 23-hour trading by the end of 2026; and DTCC is expanding processing to support 24&#215;5. So “24/7 stock trading” is closer than it used to be, even though U.S. stocks still are not literally open all weekend.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">That is exactly why AI bots for stock trading are drawing more attention now. Longer sessions create more opportunity, but also more room for slippage, bad fills, and thin overnight liquidity. FINRA says AI applications are proliferating across securities firms, including portfolio management and trading functions, but it also stresses that AI does not remove firms’ regulatory obligations or operational risks.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There is another reason to be careful: regulators are now openly warning that “AI auto-trading” is also a fraud magnet. FINRA says it has seen an increase in unregistered entities promoting auto-trading services as beginner-friendly, risk-free, and capable of consistent double-digit monthly returns. The CFTC says generative AI is making scams more convincing, Investor.gov warns that scammers exploit AI hype in social media and investment group chats, and the SEC’s Cyber and Emerging Technologies Unit lists AI-related fraud as a priority area.</span></p>
