										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.stormtherapeutics.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Storm Therapeutics</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> has recently completed a $56M Series C </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/glydways-raises-170m-to-scale-transit-technology/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round, an indicator of a new era for the treatment of a number of rare and aggressive cancers. As announced on April 16, 2026, the proceeds will be used to initiate Phase 2 clinical studies for Storm&#8217;s lead candidate, STC-15, in the hardest-to-treat cancers, precision oncology.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The commercial financing was supported by a heavyweight syndicate of investors: M Ventures, Pfizer Ventures, Taiho Ventures, and IP Group, plus the UTokyo Innovation Platform and Fast Track Initiative – all major players. It is &#8216;notable that these titans of industry would be able to join a syndicate because of the strength of support for epitranscriptomics, which so far appears poised to be the next front in oncology.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A New Scientific Frontier: Reprogramming Cancer</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Storm Therapeutics is focusing on the machinery that determines how cells transcribe their DNA, rather than attacking cancers by targeting surface proteins or genetic alterations to DNA.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200044" style="width: 410px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200044" class="wp-image-200044" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/STORM-Therapeutics.jpeg" alt="STORM Therapeutics" width="400" height="400" /><p id="caption-attachment-200044" class="wp-caption-text">Source: STORM Therapeutics</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Leading the charge for Storm is STC-15, a first-in-class oral, small-molecule METTL3 inhibitor. METTL3 is an enzyme that &#8220;methylates&#8221; mRNA, a molecular switch that, in some cancers such as sarcomas, gets stuck in the &#8220;on&#8221; position, preventing progenitor cells from differentiating into healthy tissue.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;By blocking METTL3, we&#8217;re not just killing cells; we&#8217;re reeducating them,&#8221; says Jerry McMahon. &#8220;STC-15 induces cell cycle arrest and apoptosis in the cancer cell, in essence teaching the cancer to grow and die.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/glydways-raises-170m-to-scale-transit-technology/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Glydways Raises $170M to Scale Transit Technology</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Sarcoma Challenge</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The new capital is reserved for an important milestone: the Phase 2 monotherapy study for sarcomas. Sarcomas are cancers of the bone and soft tissue (20% of adult cancers and 15% of paediatric cancers) and are very difficult to treat because they rarely harbour the &#8220;driver mutations&#8221; that modern targeted therapies, such as Genentech&#8217;s, are turning to great effect.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Storm reaffirmed that the first patient has been dosed in the current Phase 2 trial. This trial is designed to facilitate an accelerated approval pathway, a fast track that could help bring the drug to patients years earlier than traditional pathways.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The momentum is a result of a successful Phase 1 trial where STC-15 demonstrated &#8220;durable tumour regression&#8221; in various sarcoma subtypes. As opposed to many experimental therapies that have a transient effect, the durability exhibited in early trials indicates that Storm’s RNA modification technology could translate into lasting gains for patients with limited options.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Global Race for RNA</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Storm&#8217;s $56m windfall comes at a time when the biotech sector is again turning its attention to high-conviction science following a bout of market turbulence. The prospect of manipulating RNA pathways previously regarded as the &#8216;undruggable&#8217; has positioned Storm firmly on a global playing field.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Other than sarcomas, the company has more future prospects. The funding will be used to expand STC-15 into combination therapies for other major disease killers, such as NSCLC and head and neck SCC, where it will be combined with existing immunotherapies like PD-1 inhibitors.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Storm is no longer simply a promising startup but rather the first company to have ever gotten an RNA-modifying enzyme into human phase one trials. With 56 million dollars and a Phase 2 trial, it is well on its way to tackling some of the most stubborn types of cancer out there today.</span></p>
